body:
I can provide a situation where this happened to me that could line up with reason for this error (although it was happening non-deterministically for myself). 

Consider the following contract;

```C
pragma solidity ^0.5.0
contract TestScenario {
    uint public value = 2**256 - 1;
    function incrementValue() public {
        value++;
    }
}
```
and a unit test that attempts to read the value after incrementing it. Something like, 

```js
const instance = await TestScenario.new()
instance.incrementValue()
const value = (await instance.value.call()).toNumber()
```

In this case we will find that the unit test inconsistently passes and fails with the error described here

```bash
Error: Number can only safely store up to 53 bits
```

and is probably/most-likely/certainly happening because of a missing `await` on `instance.incrementValue()`. Essentially, this means that the intended increment transaction hadn't completed by the time the value was read and the initial value was too large to parse with `toNumber()`

Hope this helps, It worked for me!
